snippet.textDisplay:
The big bell at Lingyin Temple in Hangzhou, known as the "Great Bell of Lingyin" (ÁÅµÈöêÂ§ßÈíü), is a significant cultural and historical artifact housed within the temple complex. Here is more information about this notable bell:

Description:
Size and Dimensions: The Great Bell of Lingyin is a large bronze bell, weighing several tons and standing over two meters tall.

Inscription: The bell is adorned with intricate Buddhist motifs, inscriptions, and decorative patterns.

History and Significance:
Age: The exact age of the bell is not publicly documented, but it is believed to date back several centuries, possibly originating from the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644) or earlier.

Cultural Importance: The bell holds deep cultural and religious significance within Lingyin Temple and the wider Buddhist community in China.

Function and Symbolism:
Ritual Use: Traditionally, large bells like the one at Lingyin Temple are used in Buddhist rituals, ceremonies, and timekeeping within the temple complex.

Symbol of Peace and Enlightenment: In Buddhist tradition, the resonant sound of bells is considered auspicious, symbolizing peace, enlightenment, and the spreading of wisdom.

snippet.textDisplay: When I went to Hangzhou, I joined an Aussie Tour bus. There were about 40 of us. We got off at West lake, and the tour guide was taking us around. But the Aussies ignored them and stayed at a park were they were watching a 90 y.o. man doing the Qigong slow motion stretching exercises. The Aussies, all shapes, sizes and ages, stood behind him and all followed his moves. Mate, I never laughed so much in my life. The Old bloke could see the Aussie struggling behind him, and I'm pretty sure I saw a smile on his face. After about 10 minutes, the Old bloke started to do scissor kicks and jumps in the air. Most of the Aussie fell to the ground and stayed there ... the other younger ones just bent over, with hands on knees, puffing and totally out of breathe. But, the old bloke just kept going. I could not contain my laughter ... seeing all my Aussie mates on the ground, or bent over like squatted flies (and the bigger Aussies ... mate ... I thought they may have needed medical attention).

snippet.textDisplay: haha, sounds so cute. In fact, it will be much better if you just need some breathing adjustment techniques. The East attaches great importance to breath. Both China and India have a tradition of exercising the body and mind by adjusting breath. Indian yoga and Chinese Qigong are all in this way. It is a kind of self-cultivation. It is not complicated, but long-term persistence is good for physical and mental health. Therefore, in almost every park in China, there will be old people practicing
